column14:
We tested the general hypothesis that stocking treatment affects the density, growth and survival of YOY Atlantic salmon, while also accounting for other fish species and water temperature. We tested the following specific predictions: 
1) spatial variation in density will be higher in clumped- than in dispersed-stocking reaches;
 2) densities in clumped reaches will decrease with distance downstream, 
whereas densities in dispersed reaches will remain constant; 
3) YOY growth rate, as estimated by mass at the end of the summer, will increase with distance downstream in clumped reaches, but not in dispersed reaches;
 4) YOY mass will decrease as a negative power curve in relation to density;
 5) YOY survival will be higher in dispersed reaches.
